(30, 'Edu_RSS 0.2 Code and Installation', NULL, NULL, 'htm', 'Download and install Edu_RSS 0.2 software', NULL, 'Friday', '<h1>Edu_RSS 0.2 Code and Installation</h1>\n\n<p>Don\'t know what Edu_RSS is? <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/edurss02.htm\">Read this page</a> first.</p>\n\n<h2>Caveat</h2>\n\n<p>Edu_RSS 0.2 is an unfinished project. The code works fine on my site, but you may encounter undexpected issues (like some links that point to downes.ca for example). If you are dowloading and installing this, you are doing it to explore the system, rather than to set up a production environment.</p>\n\n<p>Also, please note well: <i>I am not a programmer</i>. I am a philosopher and theorist. What this means is that there will be numerous ways in which this could have been better and more efficiently coded. Please know that I appreciate this. If you want to tell me how it could have been done better (and I hope you do) please send some code along with the comment.</p>\n\n<h2>Getting Ready</h2>\n\n<p>Edu_RSS uses and runs in the same environment as the <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/midm.htm\">mIDm login system</a>. Before you install Edu_RSS, install and test mIDm according to the directions posted <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=32667\">here</a>.</p>\n\n<p>During your installation of mIDm you will configure access to the mIDm database. Edu_RSS shares this same configuration file and stores files on the same database. So once you have mIDm installed, your server environment will be set to go.</p>\n\n<h2>Perl Environment</h2>\n\n<p>I have tried to keep the use of Perl modules to a minimum, as I have no control over their development, and because you have to be a server administrator in order to install them (in other words, they\'re a pain to use). Nonetheless, the scripts below require the following Perl modules:</p>\n\n<p>\nCGI<br/>\nCGI::Carp<br/>\nXML::LibXML<br/>\nFile::Copy<br/>\nLWP<br/>\nApache::DBI()<br/>\nGD<br/>\nImage::GD::Thumbnail<br/>\n</p>\n\n<p>Most of these will already be in your system. If they are not, ask your server administrator to install them.</p>\n\n<h2>Edu_RSS Software</h2>\n\n<p>Edu_RSS emplys a set of Perl scripts and some SQL to set up your database. You should probably set up the database first. Download and run the following SQL on the same database you used for mIDm:</p>\n<ul>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/code/edurss.sql\">edurss.sql</a>\n</ul>\n<p>This SQL not only defines the database, it also contains some templates and views to get you started. You can always edit those later.</p>\n\n<p>Next, download and install the following scripts, renaming them and putting them into your web server directories as follows (The cgi-bin directory should be whatever you specified in mIDm.conf as your CGI directory):<p>\n\n<p>\ncgi-bin/<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/code/page.txt\">page.cgi</a><br/>\ncgi-bin/<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/code/mycss.txt\">mycss.cgi</a><br/>\ncgi-bin/<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/code/mytheme.txt\">mytheme.cgi</a><br/>\ncgi-bin/edurss/<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/code/edurss/harvester.pl\">page.cgi</a><br/>\ncgi-bin/edurss/<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/code/edurss/gallery.pl\">gallery.pl</a><br/>\n</p>\n\n<p>If you are using a Linux or Unix system, you will need to give these scripts execute permission (chmod 755). If you are using a Windows system, you don\'t have to do this (but I have no idea whether they\'ll run, either).</p>\n\n<p>Note: right now, you will need to edit a couple lines at the top of page.cgi to point to actual file locations in your system. Specifically, change &get_site($Site,\"/home/downess/opt-httpd-prefork-htdocs/cgi-bin/data/midm.conf\");	to the location of your configuration file and require \"/home/downess/opt-httpd-prefork-htdocs/cgi-bin/edurss/harvester.pl\" to point to your edurss subdirectory (sorry about that; it was a quick fix to make cron work properly).</p>\n\n<p>That\'s it! Your Edu_RSS system should now run. Should. It has been tested only in limited environments. Note as well that many of the views point specifically to downes.ca - check the edit views especially and change the post action=\"\" parameter to the location of your own script (you may have to use phpMyAdmin to edit view_edit in the view table to get the system off the ground).</p>\n\n<p>Bug reports, comments and cheerful notes would be warmly received. If you want to contribute to this code, your contributions are welcome.</p>\n\n\n', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'no', 'no', 'no', '1', 1136227064, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, NULL, NULL, 'code/edurss02.htm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', '2'),
(31, 'Edu_RSS 0.2 Screenshots', NULL, NULL, 'htm', NULL, NULL, 'Friday', '<h1>Edu_RSS 0.2 Screenshots</h1>\n<p>Here is what Edu_RSS 0.2 - the software I am currently using to run my website - looks like behind the scenes. Note that text size has been enlarged to make it easier to see.</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss1.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss1t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nThe main administration screen. This is what I see when I start Edu_RSS. Notice the list of items to the left - this is where I work directly with the site content.\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss2.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss2t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nCreate post. This is the screen I see most often - it is what I use to input posts for OLDaily, articles, and other content.</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss3.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss3t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nList posts. When I click on the \'list\' link to the left, this is what I see. The \'list\' screens for the other types of content look pretty much the same. Note that the list post screen allows me to both view and edit posts.</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss4.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss4t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nEdit post. Here\'s what I see when I edit a post from today\'s newsletter. When I created the post it was automatically associated with a link - I can see this link and edit it from this screen.</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss5.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss5t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nA little lower on another \'edit post\' page. This post has a number of files associated with it. The files are listed and can be viewed by clicking on the filename, or edited using the edit button. New files can be added.</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss6t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nCreate file. When I upload a file, I select the file (using the \'browse\' button and type a description. The system fills in everything else automatically for me. Note that it is automatically associated with the post I was working on.</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss7.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss7t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nFile edit. The uploaded file, with information added.</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss8.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss8t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nEdit person. The edit screens are very consistent, with few surprises to the user.\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss9.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss9t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nList page. Looks a lot like list post (except I decided to display these alphabetically). Note that pages can be published directly from the \'list\' screen, as well as from the edit screen.\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss10.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss10t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nEdit page. This is the Stephen\'s Web <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca\">home page</a> in the editor. I\'ve scrolled down a bit so you can see the use of keyword commands to dynamically create content (you can see the commands for articles, links and musings in the center column). This page can be <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?page=3\">viewed live</a>, but I prefer to publish it once a day as a static web page, to reduce the load on the server.\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss11.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss11t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nList templates. as you see, I can get by with a pretty basic set of templates.\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss12.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss12t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nEdit template. This is the top of the OLDaily RSS feed. Notice the use of PAGE_TITLE (and I will soon add an INSTITUTION command so I don\'t have to type out \"Stephen\'s Web\". Also botice the use of the 822_DATE and NOW commands, to prepare properly formatted RFC822 dates.\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss13.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss13t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nEdit page again. This page defines the OLDaily RSS 2.0 feed. I\'ve scrolled a bit to emphasize the editing screen (again, note that I\'ve enlarged to font size - normally I view this all in a single screen). Notice the use of the RSS templates for header and footer. Also notice that the entire content of the feed is defined with a few keyword commands (I could have just used one, but I wanted different rules to apply to different types of post).\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss14.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss14t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nList views. Each record (a post, an event, a link, or whatever) in Edu_RSS is displayed in its own view; there are various formats (HTML, text, list, RSS, etc.)\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss15.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss15t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nEdit view. This defines how posts in HTML will be displayed when a list of posts is collected using a keyword command. Notice the use of the date, keyword and other commands. It should be noted that while these views can be created and edited, the full set of views is included with the Edu_RSS download (if you don\'t like coding Perl you can create views and give Edu_RSS a much more attractive look or define new types of content with nested keyword commands).\n</p>\n\n<p>\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss16.jpg\"><img src=\"http://www.downes.ca/images/edurss02/ss16t.jpg\" width=300></a><br/>\nPost. This is a look at a post displayed using the view shown directly above (usually you see this format in a list of posts, but as you can see, I can specify any format I want in the page request).\n</p>\n\n<p>Well that should be enough to give you a taste of the system. If you want to see examples of the varied output the system makes possible, explore the links at the bottom of the <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/edurss02.htm\">Edu_RSS 0.2 description page</a>. </p>\n', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'no', 'no', 'no', '1', 1136231556, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, NULL, NULL, 'edurss02_screenshots.htm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', '2'),
(32, 'Edu_RSS Most Recent - RSS old', 'http://www.downes.ca/edu_rss.htm', NULL, 'rss', '<![CDATA[<strong>Notice for Edu_RSS readers</strong>: this feed has switched over from the old system to the <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/edurss02.htm\">new Edu_RSS 0.2</a> harvester. There will be more links than usual for a couple of days until the new system catches up. This new feed is also available as <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/edu_rss.xml\">edu_rss.xml</a>.]]>', NULL, 'Friday', '<keyword db=link;number=20;format=rss;all;sort=crdate DESC;status=primary>', 'none', NULL, 'RSS02_top', 'RSS02_bottom', 'no', 'no', 'no', '1', 1136310142, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, NULL, NULL, 'edu_rss.rss', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', '2'),
(33, 'MyGlu', NULL, NULL, 'htm', 'It\'s like SuprGlu - but without SuperGlu', NULL, 'Friday', '<h1>MyGlu</h1>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.suprglu.com/\">SuprGlu</a> is a great site, but the problem with it is that you have to use the SuprGlu website. If you want to tinker with the code, add feeds from your friends, put the content right in your webpage, or whatever, you\'re out of luck.</p>\n\n<p>MyGlu solves all that. Using code from <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/edurss02.htm\">Edu_RSS</a> (which was way ahead of SuprGlu in this sort of thing, in case people have forgotten), MyGlu allows you to define your own list of feeds (including your own <a href=\"http://del.icio.us\">del.icio.us</a> feeds), merge them into a single feed, and place the results on your web page (in a few days I\'ll add RSS and Javascript output as well).</p>\n\n<p>MyGlu not only aggregates feeds, it also filters them according to your specifications. So, for example, you could aggregate your posts, photos and bookmarks with the term \'Amsterdam\' in them.</p>\n\n<p>Here\'s how it works:</p>\n\n<p>- Define the list of feeds you want to harvest in an OPML file. Right now I\'m using a really basic OPML file (but I\'ll probably add some stuff to it in a bit). <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/myglutest.xml\">Here\'s an example</a>.</p>\n\n<p>- Put the OPML file on your server. <b>Hint</b>: don\'t have a server? Input the text into blogger or any other blogging site (be sure you input in \'show HTML\' mode, so your angle brackets aren\'t converted).</p>\n\n<p>- In your web page (or in your Blogger template, or wherever) insert an iframe calling the MyGlu script. The URL you use to call the script will specify the OPML file to use as well as your filtering terms. Like this:</p>\n\n<p> Here\'s the URL: <br/>http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/myglu.cgi?feedlist=http://your_opml_file&description=your_content_filter\n</p>\n\n<p> Here\'s what the iframe code looks like:<br/>\n\n&lt;iframe width=1000 height=800 src=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/myglu.cgi?description=your_content_filter&feedlist=http://your_opml_file\"&gt;\n</p>\n\n<p>Pretty simple, eh? <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/mygluframe.htm\">Here\'s a working example</a></p>\n\n<p>Now, some things:</p>\n\n<p>You can filter for category (sort of; the different service all define their tags differently so I will add them as I encounter them) by using tag=your_content_filter instead of description=your_content_filter</p>\n\n<p>The filters are <a href=\"http://sitescooper.org/tao_regexps.html\">regular expressions</a>, which gives you a <i>very</i> flexible filter.</p>\n\n<p>I am limiting the number of URLs you can aggregate to 10. This is because I don\'t want to kill my server.</p>\n\n<p>MyGlu checks the date of posts and displays only those from the last day. Some feeds do not datestamp their posts; MyGlu can either accept them and print them all (that\'s what it does not) or reject them.</p>\n\n<p>I use caching as well, again to save my filter. Feeds will be harvested no more frequently than once an hour (so your links might not update right away; watch for that) and your output page will not be generated any more than once an hour.</p>\n\n<p>I will also be adding some code that will allow you to <i>upload your feed to Blogger</i> as a post (it will take me about an hour to code, but I\'ve run out of time today).</p>\n\n<p>Watch this page for changes.</p>\n\n<h2>Code</h2>\n\n<p>Code? Of <i>course</i> there\'s code. <a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/code/myglu.txt\">Here\'s the code</a>.</p>\n\n<p>To run this on your own server (please run this on your own server): download the code, change the extension from .txt to .cgi, upload the code to your own server, chmod to 755. The code requires two cache subdirectories under the script: myglu/feedcache and myglu/clientcache. Like this:</p>\n\n<p>cgi-bin/myglu.cgi<br/>\ncgi-bin/myglu/feedcache/<br/>\ncgi-bin/myglu/clientcache/<br/>\n</p>\n\nThat\'s it for now. I am always happy to get comments. I will add features by request for the next little while.</p>\n\n<h2>Link and Comments</h2>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=33198\">Discussion and Comment Here</a>\n', 'none', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'no', 'no', 'no', '1', 1136850478, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 7, NULL, NULL, 'myglu.htm', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', '2'),
