" border=\"0\"></a>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n    <!-- 75 percent width column, aligned to the right -->\r\n    <div class=\"width75 floatRight\">\r\n\r\n\r\n      <!-- Gives the gradient block -->\r\n      <div class=\"gradient\">\r\n\r\n\r\n       <br /><p class=\"login\"> <script language=\"Javascript\">login_box();</script></p><h2>Discussion Threads</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>April 6, 2011</p>\r\n\r\n<!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55156\">Re: The Problem with Social Media</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nbigenhoc, \r\nApril 4, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">I have also been thinking about this very issue with recent work I have been doing in bullying and the latest video to go viral- Rebecca Black\'s Friday. I have been floored by the negative comments and the general offensive, mean and personal attacks that are largely made anonymously and/or without any knowledge of the effect their attacks have on the targeted individual. So while I am also sympathetic with Gary\'s point, I must agree that we can\'t blame the tools that allow the \"social\" to flow and interact. This is a problem with people and not the tools. I believe that we have been nurturing a general culture of meanness for many years. I am also fitting the urge to look at this issue from a biological perspective of evolution. I am reminded of a time when I was fishing as a kid and caught a small shark (3-4 feet). I was amazed by the spectacle as the shark came near the surface and I saw a school of larger and smaller sharks all attacking the one that was on my line. This shark was hurt, moved differently than all the others because I was reeling it in. It stood out and was an easy target. The recent video by Rebecca Black that went viral because of negative comments is not that different. A few very cutting, mean comments and the feeding frenzy ensued. Have we not evolved much socially beyond the feeding behavior of sharks? This is a blog post I have wanted to write but this will have to do for now. I am saddened by the general hate and meanness I see expressed every day. The fact that the crowd mentality can take over so quickly just means we have a lot more growth and evolving to do as a society. Limiting the interactions of the Social is not the solution. Rather, we must take it upon ourselves to become actively involved in making such social spaces more positive and that constructive criticism rules the day when you don\'t agree. </a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55156&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55163\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55162&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55164&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55163>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nRoy Williams, \r\nApril 4, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Indeed, and citations are i) bluint instruments, and ii) open to some abuse. \r<br/>\r<br/>What if ... \r<br/>Social network analysis profiles or footprints could be used instead, and coded in some way to make different domains of networking clearly evident?  Could this differentiate visually, and clearly, between academic citations by others/ academic citations by self/ RSS feeds/ responses to postings/ links to postings, etc, etc?  \r<br/>\r<br/>For instance, what would one do with the data from OLD \'citations\', would it be one category, on several distinct ones? \r<br/>\r<br/>Then the academic could be asked to attend a conversation (in person, online, open, restricted ...) to discuss their footprint/ profile, preferably across an interactive, live, timeline.  That could be a useful investment in HE \'knowledge infrastructure\', no? \r<br/>\r<br/></a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55150\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55149&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55151&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55150>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55134\">Re: When Will Educators Get Serious About Gaming? </a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nJohn Thomas, \r\nApril 3, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Bruce Dixon\'s reasoning doesn\'t seem odd to me.\r<br/>\r<br/>Despite computer games\' long history in education, they are not part of mainstream practise â€“ most teachers don\'t use them. Some attempts to introduce them also seem to have reached \'dead ends\'. The busy assessment driven curriculum of today\'s schools leaves little room for the free ranging thematic approach of the 1980s when educational adventure games could be the motivational centrepiece of cross-curricular activity in the classroom. \r<br/>\r<br/>There may be a great deal of talk about the value of computer games in education, but we have a long way to go before their effective use is evident in most classrooms.\r<br/>\r<br/></a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55134&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55146\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55145&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55147&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55146>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nStephen Downes, \r\nApril 2, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">It is an interesting idea, limiting the number of publications to just one. That would curtail the \'counting publications\' method of assessing academics. But it would probably revert to \'counting cites\'. </a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55143\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55142&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55144&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55143>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55137\">Re: Andorra</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nGerry White, \r\nApril 2, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Dear Stephen\r<br/>\r<br/>I think Andorra is probably one of my favourite places. I remember the absolute beauty of the place and its features together with the sheer immensity of the surroundings and landscape. And you have captured all of that in your magnificent pictures which I thoroughly enjoyed. Many thanks once again for sharing your scenes pictures with us and for your exquisite selection of shots.\r<br/>\r<br/>Cheers\r<br/>Gerry White\r<br/>Down Under</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55137&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55140\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55139&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55141&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55140>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55137\">Re: Andorra</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\npaulbmckenzie, \r\nApril 2, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">You\'ve lost weight!</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55137&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55139\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55138&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55140&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55139>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55133\">Re: The Innovation Mismatch: Smart Capital and Education Innovation</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nRSmallwood, \r\nApril 1, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">\"No Child Left Behind\", started with a lie and promoted by \"simple fixers\" (in my book, anyone who thinks all truth, knowledge, and skills can be boiled down to standardized multiple choice tests), has so distorted American education so much that Weiss\'s article makes complete sense.  If everything in education is about maximizing test scores, then teach to the tests or change the tests.  Who cares about real education or real learning?  Real education means getting messy by dealing with ideas &amp; concepts that may not have \"A\" right answer.  Real learning means getting so comfortable with those same ideas &amp; concepts that you can accept that your \"right\" answer is not the \"right\" for someone else, besides you keep reevaluating your answer anyway.\r<br/>\r<br/>The United States is leading the way but I see Canada sliding along (if not stepping along) right behind.  We are in a federal election right now and Riderland (Saskatchewan) will have one this fall.  Wouldn\'t it be nice to have a debate about what is important for future generations to be able to do?  Wouldn\'t it be interesting, if not down right FUN, have an educational system that focuses on creativity, analysis, individualism (both in progress &amp; content), problem solving, and innovation.  It would be very hard.  The \"system\" and many of its practitioners would need to under go a total transformation.  Yes, indeed, it would be fun.</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55133&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55136\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55135&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55137&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55136>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nRoy Williams, \r\nApril 1, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Fair point.  I have not met anyone else who can do what this particular person did.  It\'s an easy game to mimic, and a really difficult one to do well. So this guy was an exception, as well as being exceptional. \r<br/>\r<br/>There is also a very large group of \'intellectual entrepreneurs\' who are really \'intellectual recyclers\', and who conduct not much more than \'academic tourism\', under the guise of teaching (and publication). \r<br/>\r<br/>I often wonder if it would be a good idea to limit the number of papers academics can publish - one a year would be an interesting discipline. (Presentations excepted). \r<br/>\r<br/></a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55132\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55131&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55133&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55132>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55126\">Re: Don\'t Filter Me - Letter to Rochester Community Schools </a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nmgozaydin, \r\nApril 1, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">we, supposedly good adults, have a right to stop bad things at the internet until children reach to age 18 .\r<br/>After that they can decide themselves.\r<br/>If tomorrow thieves start their own websites what are you going to do .\r<br/>It is not far away. It will be sooner than you think .</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55126&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55130\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55129&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55131&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55130>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nStephen Downes, \r\nMarch 31, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Well I don\'t think being an open thinker is equivalent to being someone who makes no assertions. I make assertions all the time, yet I think I\'m an open thinker. What I do is make assertions and test them, make assertions and test them - and I\'m open about the assertions, and the tests, and if evidence does not support my assertion, I adjust my assertion accordingly. Being an open thinker is about being honest about what you know, what you don\'t know, and how you go about telling the difference.\r<br/>\r<br/>I\'ve met people who enquire simply by asking questions. It can be annoying, because they think they\'re being Socratic, but the questioning gets circular very quickly. Or the questions are actually frames, designed to lead people a certain way, and because the person won\'t actually make an assertion, you have to go through the unnecessary and tiresome work of extracting the assertions and the frame from the implications contained in the question. And there\'s a whole breed of \'intellectual entrepreneur\' that makes its living by not actually asserting anything at all, by merely using the right words and concepts, so they sound business-friendly and are in fact non-threatening.</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55122\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55121&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55123&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55122>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nRoy Williams, \r\nMarch 31, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">> intellectual entrepreneurs\" seem more often to be promoting their ....\r<br/>\r<br/>OK, fair point. What\'s interesting is precisely what you have pinpointed - that the difference is often difficult to spot. \r<br/>\r<br/>There is a great aphorism about publishing: \"you may indulge your reader, but you may not indulge yourself\".  \r<br/>\r<br/>Can we use this to distinguish between \'open thinkers\' and \'intellectual entrepreneurs\'?  I can think of one example, my philosophy prof., Johann Degenaar, who in all the years I studied with him never made an assertion - he just tried to find the next question. </a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55118\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55117&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55119&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55118>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nStephen Downes, \r\nMarch 30, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">> surely you recognise the difference between openness and ownership, and between intellectual entrepreneurs (if you have to) and financial entrepreneurs? \r<br/>\r<br/>I recognize the difference between ownership and openness.\r<br/>\r<br/>The differences between the two types of \"entrepreneurs\" are more difficult to spot, especially as the \"intellectual entrepreneurs\" seem more often to be promoting their books, appearances, programs, etc., than anything else.</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55117\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55116&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55118&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55117>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nRoy Williams, \r\nMarch 29, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">I am sure we are all naive in our own sweet ways. \r<br/>\r<br/>To the point though ... \r<br/>\r<br/>surely you recognise the difference between openness and ownership, and between intellectual entrepreneurs (if you have to) and financial entrepreneurs? </a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55112\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55111&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55113&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55112>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nAndrew Dalgliesh, \r\nMarch 28, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Stephen - we\'ve also been going through an interesting process of redefining the role of the \"expert\" in the transtion to allow/support/facilitate the use of our systems for user-generated content - at this stage mostly aimed at teachers developing and sharing content across a system of 35,000+ staff. Student creation/remixing/sharing etc is next on the agenda :)\r<br/>\r<br/>One big change was that our content experts begand to change from beign solely gatekeepers of \"quality control\" to facilitators in a wide community of professionals, articulating and promoting standards, modelling best practice, mentoring and coaching.\r<br/>\r<br/>This change was prompted a few years back by this article about, of all things, the role of a Town Organist in a facility funded by public money and how we can leverage these kind of investments for the common good:\r<br/>\r<br/>http://www.themonthly.com.au/nation-reviewed-john-hirst-comment-public-goods-amp-pipe-organs-1415#</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55110\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55109&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55111&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55110>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107\">Re: Revolutions in Higher Education: how many dimensions of openness?</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nwaltl, \r\nMarch 28, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Call me quaint; call me naive. But, call me happy</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55109\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55108&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55110&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55109>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55074\">Re: Media Converter for Mac</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nFrank Lowney, \r\nMarch 27, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">Here\'s the home page for this app:\r<br/>\r<br/>http://media-converter.sourceforge.net/index.html\r<br/>\r<br/></a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55074&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55108\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55107&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55109&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55108>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55094\">ONLINE Education for the world.</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nmgozaydin, \r\nMarch 25, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">It is good that everybody tries to solve the education problem of the world.\r<br/>Solutions are many .\r<br/>So far best technology is ONLINE Technology.\r<br/>Models are many .\r<br/>Principle of ONLINE is  as I understand it  :\r<br/>1.- Spend many for original development of the course\r<br/>2.- Reach out to millions in order to bring cost per person to nill.\r<br/>\r<br/>Examples :\r<br/>1.- Assume one online course of Harvard is followed by 100,000 students in the world per year. In 5 years 500,000 students.\r<br/>Each can pay at least $ 20 for one course.\r<br/>So funding is $ 10 million .\r<br/>With that money Harvard would be very pleased. \r<br/>2.- But in order to have 100,000 students in the world many many universities should adopt the course for their students.\r<br/>Only thing is organisation ?\r<br/>\r<br/>Second Model \r<br/>1.- There is academicearth.org with courses from MIT, Harvard, Yale etc.\r<br/>     Any university in the world adopt their courses for their students.\r<br/>     But local university makes the superfvision, homeworks, finals.\r<br/>2.- But credit and degrees at the end will be  given by the local university.\r<br/>3.- This is 100 % free. But one should donate to MIT, Yale etc too.\r<br/>This model I provide :\r<br/>www.globalonlineuniversitiesconsortium.org\r<br/>That costs me onoly $ 100 per year. Zero to students and only a supervisor salary to universities.\r<br/>This model must be supported by everybody in the world. Particularly by UNESCO, UN .\r<br/>mgozaydin@hotmail.com</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55094&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55099\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55098&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55100&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55099>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=42878\">Re: MoDazzle: Access Facebook</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nJRodgers96, \r\nMarch 25, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">How to unblock facebook on school Lenovo laptops</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=42878&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55098\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55097&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55099&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55098>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=53424\">Re: Types of Meaning</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nSoe, \r\nMarch 24, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">thanks sir for the article..</a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=53424&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55097\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55096&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55098&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55097>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post --><!-- Begin Post -->\r\n<h4><a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55009\">Re: The Learning Design Support Environment (LDSE)</a></h4>\r\n<p class=\"byline\"><span class=\"bylinespan\">\r\nd.laurillard, \r\nMarch 24, 2011\r\n</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"comment\">True â€“ the \'whole infrastructure\' is a big project. We have a lesser ambition. This is a \'design support tool\' - so we\'re not yet intending to work through to the full implementation of what is designed, which would require all the infrastructure features you suggest, and more. Our aim is to begin by capturing how teachers describe their designs, but using a structured format that can be subjected to computational analysis. If we can do that in a way that teachers are comfortable with, and able to use â€“ an empirical question and a challenging design problem â€“ this would enable teachers to find, share, adopt and adapt each others\' designs. \r<br/>\r<br/>Here\'s a trial site for the part of our project that\'s working out how best to support such an activity: tinyurl.com/ldsepatterns â€“ Please try it and give us your comments.\r<br/>\r<br/>Enabling teachers to capture and share their pedagogy is a more modest, and perhaps more tractable ambition than tackling the whole infrastructure. If it succeeds then it would be a good basis for building the infrastructure that teachers might be glad to use. It\'s not an end-to-end solution, but the project has taken on many of the \"sticky hard issues\" that other projects tend to avoid. And it\'s a \'support environment\', intended to help teachers think through and model some of the other points you raise, before they go ahead with implementing their teaching idea.\r<br/></a> [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55009&format=full\">Comment</a>]\r\n[<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55096\">Permalink</a>]\r\n [<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55095&format=html\">Previous</a>][<a  href=\"http://www.downes.ca/cgi-bin/page.cgi?post=55097&format=html\">Next</a>] <admin post,55096>\r\n</p>\r\n<!-- End Post -->      </div>\r\n\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\n  </div>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!-- FOOTER: Site footer for links, copyright, etc. -->\r\n<div id=\"footer\">\r\n  <div id=\"width\">\r\n    <span class=\"floatLeft\">\r\n\r\n<a rel=\"license\" href=\"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/\"><img alt=\"Creative Commons License\" style=\"border-width:0\" src=\"http://i.creativecommons.org/l/by-nc-sa/3.0/88x31.png\" /></a>.\r\n\r\n    </span>\r\n\r\n    <span class=\"floatRight\">\r\n<p>Copyright 2010 Stephen Downes ~ \r\n\r\n		Contact: <a  href=\"mailto:stephen@downes.ca\">stephen@downes.ca</a><br />\r\nCSS design adapted from <a  href=\"http://fullahead.org\" title=\"Goto Fullahead\">Fullahead</a> <span class=\"grey\">|</span>\r\n      valid <a  href=\"http://validator.w3.org/check?uri=referer\" title=\"Validate XHTML\">X